<subSubSection id="C3126543FFDAFFD961C4FB920593F20A" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BB736C8FFDAFFD961C4FB920593F20A" blockId="38.[151,1437,870,1977]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="B97CEADAFFDAFFD961C4FB92058CF37B" bold="true" box="[199,467,1122,1148]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Differential Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Among Brazilian species, recognized by the combination of small size (ca. 
<quantity id="4CF09B2DFFDAFFD9642BFB9301CFF37A" box="[1320,1424,1123,1149]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.49" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="mm" value="2.49">2.49 mm</quantity>
), the black to bronze dorsal color, the pronotum with shallow impressions and dense, rather uniform punctuation, the elytral interstriae narrow ridges, often forming zig-zag pattern, the pronotal shape, and the male genitalia (
<figureCitation id="13332A4DFFDAFFD9646CFB5B04E9F3EE" captionStart="FIGURES 46–47" captionStartId="75.[151,264,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[208,1390,189,1902]" captionTargetId="figure-15@75.[185,1402,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="75" captionText="FIGURES 46–47. Habitus and male genitalia of holotypes. 46. Hydrochus xingu n. sp. 47. Hydrochus constrictus n. sp." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5043332" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5043332/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 46</figureCitation>
; described below). Differentiation from other similarly small sized species with similarly shaped pronotum will require dissection of males.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3126543FFDAFFD961C4FAE60482F092" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BB736C8FFDAFFD961C4FAE605AEF2E2" blockId="38.[151,1437,870,1977]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="B97CEADAFFDAFFD961C4FAE6050EF237" bold="true" box="[199,337,1302,1328]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Description</emphasis>
. Size: 
<typeStatus id="54B3886AFFDAFFD960A7FAE70659F236" box="[420,518,1303,1329]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">holotype</typeStatus>
(length/width, mm): body (length to elytral apices) 2.49/0.94; head width 0.64; pronotum l/w 0.62/0.66; PA 0.62; PB 0.54; elytra 1.61/0.94. Habitus as illustrated (
<figureCitation id="13332A4DFFDAFFD9653CFACB00CCF251" box="[1087,1171,1339,1366]" captionStart="FIGURES 46–47" captionStartId="75.[151,264,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[208,1390,189,1902]" captionTargetId="figure-15@75.[185,1402,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="75" captionText="FIGURES 46–47. Habitus and male genitalia of holotypes. 46. Hydrochus xingu n. sp. 47. Hydrochus constrictus n. sp." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5043332" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5043332/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 46</figureCitation>
). Dorsum black to grey to bronze, with very slight iridescence, elytra with black spots. Legs brown. Dorsal punctuation dense. Punctation on elytra ca. 2x that of pronotum. Elytra interstriae narrow ridges, often forming zig-zag pattern, to ca. 0.5x strial puncture diameter, or less. Interstria 9 
<superScript id="7C7D9B80FFDAFFD96338FA560617F2B3" attach="left" box="[571,584,1446,1460]" fontSize="6" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">th</superScript>
more convex than others, overhanging 10 
<superScript id="7C7D9B80FFDAFFD96518FA560077F2B3" attach="left" box="[1051,1064,1446,1460]" fontSize="6" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">th</superScript>
interstria. Usual area of callus on 5 
<superScript id="7C7D9B80FFDAFFD961A6FA3A04EDF2DF" attach="left" box="[165,178,1482,1496]" fontSize="6" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">th</superScript>
very weakly raised, if at all.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB736C8FFDAFFD961C4FA1F053CF156" blockId="38.[151,1437,870,1977]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Pronotum length less than width (ratio ca. 33/35), densely coarsely punctate, of quite uniform puncture size; widest at anterior margin, narrowed at base, sides weakly sinuate, smooth; anterior margin slightly bisinuate; depressions shallow.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB736C8FFDAFFD961C4F9AB006AF19E" blockId="38.[151,1437,870,1977]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Elytra with spaces between strial punctures narrow walls to ca. 0.5x their diameter; apices slightly produced, separately rounded in dorsal view, in lateral view outer margin without angulation.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB736C8FFDAFFD961C4F95300E2F1BA" blockId="38.[151,1437,870,1977]" box="[199,1213,1699,1725]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Ventral characters: Mentum punctate, with central depression; submentum without foveae.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB736C8FFDAFFD961C4F9370482F092" blockId="38.[151,1437,870,1977]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation id="13332A4DFFDAFFD96075F9370598F1E5" box="[374,455,1735,1762]" captionStart="FIGURES 46–47" captionStartId="75.[151,264,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[208,1390,189,1902]" captionTargetId="figure-15@75.[185,1402,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="75" captionText="FIGURES 46–47. Habitus and male genitalia of holotypes. 46. Hydrochus xingu n. sp. 47. Hydrochus constrictus n. sp." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5043332" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5043332/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 46</figureCitation>
) general characters: genitalia without parameres; basal piece elongate, nearly straight in both dorsal/ventral and lateral views, basal 3/5 thickened, markedly arcuate in lateral view, distal ½ thin, apex bifid, distal piece issuing from between bifurcations; distal piece elongate, in lateral view very slightly sinuate, decreasing slightly in width from base to apex, apex slightly widened and bearing minute tapering process, in dorsal/ventral views very gradually decreasing in width from base to apex, apex truncate; basal piece/distal piece length ratio ca. 50/11.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3126543FFDAFFD861C4F86F0582F7B6" lastPageId="39" lastPageNumber="40" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BB736C8FFDAFFD961C4F86F07FEF0BE" blockId="38.[151,1437,870,1977]" box="[199,929,1951,1977]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="B97CEADAFFDAFFD961C4F86F0517F0BE" bold="true" box="[199,328,1951,1977]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Etymology</emphasis>
. Named in reference to the geographical distribution.
</paragraph>
